XVIII. Ι am not surprised therefore that many centuries ago almost innumerable kinds of artificial wine have becn invented, which we will now specify‚ all of them being used for medicinal purposes. In an earlier volume we stated the method of making omphacium, which is used for unguents. What is called vine—flower wine is made from the claret vine, that is the wild vine, by steeping two pounds of the flowers of this plant in a jar of must3 30 days after- wards they are changed. Beside this the root and the grape-skins of the claret-vine are used in dressing leather. These grape-skins‚ a little after the blossom has gone off, provide a remarkable specific for cooling attacks of feverish heat in cases of disease, being said to be of an extremely cold nature. A portion of these grapes die off from the heat before the rest—these are called midsummer grapes3 the whole of them never come to matursty, and if a bunch in an unripe state before it completely withers is fed to poultry it produces in them a distaste for stealing grapes.

XIX. The first of the artificial wines, which is called weak wine, is made from real wine in the following manner: ten quarts of white must and half that quantity of water are kept boiling till a considerable amount of the water is boiled away. Other people put in five quarts of sea-water and the same amount of rain—water and leave the mixture in the sun for 40 days to evaporate. This drink is given to invalids for whom it is feared that wine may be harmful.
